keywords = {Smart cities, Individualizing, Expectations, Quality of life, Rhetoric, Wellbeing},
abstract = {Smart cities appear to offer a way of fixing common urban problems and increase quality of life for inhabitants. Despite critiques that question the benevolence of smart technology, their solutionist rhetoric continues to gain popularity and investment across the world. In response, this paper investigates the discursive frames shaping life in the Singaporean Smart Nation, which is used as an example of an intelligent technology-focused urban environment, and explores the links between this rhetoric and the quality of life of inhabitants. First, ongoing research is outlined, using the Foucault-inspired obliged freedom framework for qualitative discourse analysis, to tease out the expectations created of citizens by the smart nation project. Through interviews, an online survey, and government documents, this work demonstrates the individualizing and neoliberal nature of the rhetoric that reaches inhabitants. This highlights the potential of the techno-social process of development, creating new and deeper means of ensuring compliance in smart cities, which may not be beneficial to the populations within. It then considers how these expectations could interact with the wellbeing of the inhabitants to question the current form that the digitally enhanced urban environment is taking in Singapore, and sets up avenues for future research.}
}
